                'body' => "## What Are Peptides?\n\nPeptides are short chains of amino acids, typically comprising 2\u201350 residues, linked by peptide bonds. They exist throughout nature and play critical roles in biological signaling, hormone regulation, and cellular communication.\n\nUnlike proteins, which are larger and more complex, peptides are small enough to be synthesized in a laboratory and studied for their specific biological effects. This makes them a valuable tool in research settings.\n\n## Key Terminology\n\n- **Reconstitution** \u2014 The process of dissolving lyophilized (freeze-dried) peptide powder into a sterile solution for study\n- **Lyophilization** \u2014 Freeze-drying that removes water to preserve peptide stability\n- **Bacteriostatic Water** \u2014 Sterile water containing 0.9% benzyl alcohol, commonly used for reconstitution\n- **Purity** \u2014 The percentage of the desired peptide in a sample, measured by HPLC\n- **Assay** \u2014 A test method to determine peptide content and purity\n\n## Research Best Practices\n\nProper documentation is essential. Keep detailed records of sourcing, storage conditions, reconstitution dates, and observations. This ensures reproducibility and supports the broader research community.\n\n### Before You Begin\n\n- Verify your source through community reviews and lab test results\n- Understand the legal status of any compound in your jurisdiction\n- Ensure you have proper equipment: sterile vials, syringes, bacteriostatic water, storage containers\n- Set up a clean, organized workspace\n\n## Building Knowledge Gradually\n\nStart with well-characterized, commonly studied peptides. Read published research, compare findings across multiple sources, and engage with the community to learn from experienced researchers.",
