                'body' => "## Why Proper Reconstitution Matters\n\nReconstitution is the process of dissolving lyophilized (freeze-dried) peptide powder into a sterile solution. Doing this correctly preserves peptide integrity, ensures accurate dosing, and maintains sterility.\n\nImproper technique can lead to peptide degradation, contamination, or inaccurate concentrations \u2014 all of which compromise research results.\n\n## Choosing the Right Solvent\n\n### Bacteriostatic Water\n\nBacteriostatic water (0.9% benzyl alcohol in water) is the most common choice. The benzyl alcohol inhibits bacterial growth, allowing multiple uses from a single vial over several days or weeks.\n\n### Sterile Water vs. Bacteriostatic Water\n\n- **Sterile water** \u2014 Use only for single-dose applications. It contains no preservative and should be used immediately after reconstitution.\n- **Bacteriostatic water** \u2014 Preferred for multi-use vials. It remains sterile for up to 28 days after first use when stored properly.\n\n## Step-by-Step Protocol\n\n- Clean all surfaces and materials with alcohol\n- Allow alcohol to evaporate fully before opening vials\n- Inject solvent slowly to minimize foaming\n- Swirl gently \u2014 never shake or vortex\n- Inspect for particles or cloudiness before use\n- Refrigerate immediately after reconstitution\n\n## Common Mistakes to Avoid\n\n- **Shaking the vial** \u2014 Creates bubbles and can denature the peptide\n- **Using too much or too little solvent** \u2014 Affects concentration accuracy\n- **Reusing a syringe** \u2014 Risks contamination\n- **Storing at room temperature** \u2014 Accelerates degradation\n\n## Storage After Reconstitution\n\nMost reconstituted peptides remain stable for 7\u201314 days at 2\u20138\u00b0C. Always check the specific peptide\u2019s stability profile, as some degrade faster than others. Discard if the solution appears cloudy or contains particulates.",
