                    ],
                ],
                'body' => "## Why Purity Matters\n\nPurity is one of the most critical factors in peptide research. Impurities can confound results, introduce variability, and compromise the validity of your findings.\n\nA peptide with 98% purity contains 2% impurities, which could include truncated sequences, oxidation products, or residual solvents from synthesis.\n\n## HPLC Analysis\n\nHigh-Performance Liquid Chromatography (HPLC) is the gold standard for purity analysis. The chromatogram shows a main peak at the retention time of the target peptide.\n\n### What to Look For\n\n- **Single dominant peak** \u2014 Indicates high purity\n- **Symmetrical peak shape** \u2014 Suggests a homogeneous product\n- **No fronting or tailing** \u2014 Avoids ambiguity in integration\n- **Baseline separation** \u2014 Ensures accurate quantification\n\n## Mass Spectrometry (MS)\n\nMass spectrometry confirms peptide identity by measuring its molecular weight. The measured mass should match the theoretical mass.\n\n### Acceptable Tolerance\n\nA mass accuracy within \u00b10.5 Da is generally acceptable for most research peptides. Larger deviations may indicate incorrect synthesis or degradation.\n\n## Certificate of Analysis (COA)\n\nA COA from an independent laboratory provides documented evidence of purity and identity. Verify that:\n\n- The batch number matches your product\n- The testing date is recent\n- The purity meets your requirements\n- The lab is accredited and reputable\n\n## Red Flags\n\n- No COA available or refusal to provide one\n- Purity claims above 99% without supporting data\n- Vague or incomplete testing documentation\n- Significantly lower prices than market average",
