                'body' => "## Storage Fundamentals\n\nPeptide stability depends on temperature, light exposure, humidity, and time. Proper storage preserves peptide integrity and ensures reliable research outcomes.\n\n### Lyophilized (Freeze-Dried) Peptides\n\nLyophilized peptides are more stable than reconstituted ones but still require proper storage:\n\n- Store at -20\u00b0C for long-term stability\n- Keep away from direct light\n- Minimize exposure to humidity\n- Avoid repeated temperature changes\n\n## Reconstituted Peptide Storage\n\nOnce reconstituted, peptides become more susceptible to degradation:\n\n- Refrigerate at 2\u20138\u00b0C\n- Use within 7\u201314 days for most peptides\n- Some peptides may require shorter timeframes\n- Never freeze reconstituted peptides unless specified\n\n## Avoiding Freeze-Thaw Cycles\n\nRepeated freezing and thawing degrades peptides. If you need to store reconstituted peptides for longer periods:\n\n- Divide into single-use aliquots before freezing\n- Thaw only the amount needed for each use\n- Discard unused portions after thawing\n\n## Environmental Factors\n\n### Light\n\nMany peptides are photosensitive. Store in amber vials or opaque containers. Avoid prolonged exposure to light during handling.\n\n### Humidity\n\nMoisture absorption can lead to hydrolysis and degradation. Use desiccant packs in storage containers and allow vials to reach room temperature before opening to prevent condensation.\n\n### Temperature Stability\n\nSome peptides have different stability profiles. Always consult published data or manufacturer recommendations for specific storage conditions. When in doubt, colder storage is generally better for lyophilized material.",
