                'body' => "## The Research Landscape\n\nThe peptide research field is growing rapidly. Staying informed requires knowing where to look and how to evaluate what you find.\n\n## Finding Research\n\n### Key Databases\n\n- **PubMed** \u2014 The most comprehensive biomedical literature database\n- **Google Scholar** \u2014 Broad search with citation tracking\n- **ResearchGate** \u2014 Direct access to authors and full-text papers\n- **PubMed Central (PMC)** \u2014 Free full-text versions of many studies\n\n### Search Tips\n\n- Use both common names and systematic names\n- Include CAS numbers for precision\n- Filter by publication date for recent research\n- Review cited references for foundational studies\n\n## Evaluating Study Quality\n\nNot all studies are equal. Consider:\n\n### Sample Size\n\nSmall studies (n < 10) may have limited statistical power. Larger sample sizes generally provide more reliable results.\n\n### Controls\n\nLook for proper control groups. Placebo-controlled, double-blind studies are the gold standard for clinical research.\n\n### Statistical Analysis\n\nCheck that appropriate statistical tests were used and that effect sizes are reported alongside p-values.\n\n## Understanding Study Limitations\n\nEvery study has limitations. Responsible interpretation requires acknowledging them:\n\n- Animal models may not translate directly\n- In vitro results need in vivo confirmation\n- Short-term studies may miss long-term effects\n- Funding sources can introduce bias\n\n## Building a Reference Library\n\nOrganize your research findings for easy reference:\n\n- Use a reference manager like Zotero or Mendeley\n- Tag studies by peptide, mechanism, and findings\n- Annotate PDFs with your observations\n- Share relevant findings with the community",
