                ],
                'body' => "## Introduction to Peptide Signaling\n\nPeptides exert their biological effects primarily through interaction with cell surface receptors. The most common class is G protein-coupled receptors (GPCRs), which represent the largest family of membrane receptors in the human genome.\n\n## Receptor Binding\n\nWhen a peptide ligand binds to its cognate receptor, it induces a conformational change that activates intracellular signaling pathways. This process is highly specific: even small changes in peptide sequence can dramatically alter receptor affinity and activation.\n\n### Key Concepts\n\n- **Affinity** \u2014 The strength of binding between a peptide and its receptor\n- **Efficacy** \u2014 The ability of a bound peptide to produce a biological response\n- **Selectivity** \u2014 The preference of a peptide for one receptor subtype over others\n\n## Signal Transduction Pathways\n\nUpon activation, GPCRs interact with heterotrimeric G proteins, which in turn modulate various effectors:\n\n- **Adenylyl cyclase** \u2014 Regulates cAMP levels\n- **Phospholipase C** \u2014 Generates IP3 and DAG\n- **Ion channels** \u2014 Modulates membrane potential\n\n## Implications for Research\n\nUnderstanding these mechanisms allows researchers to predict peptide effects, design analogues with improved properties, and identify potential therapeutic applications. The structure-activity relationship (SAR) of peptides is a cornerstone of modern peptide research.",
