                'body' => "## Chemical Stability of Peptides\n\nPeptides are susceptible to various chemical degradation pathways. Understanding these is essential for proper handling, storage, and experimental design.\n\n## Major Degradation Pathways\n\n### Hydrolysis\n\nPeptide bonds can undergo hydrolysis, particularly at aspartic acid residues. This reaction is accelerated by acidic or basic conditions and elevated temperatures.\n\n### Oxidation\n\nMethionine, cysteine, and tryptophan residues are particularly susceptible to oxidation. This can occur during storage, handling, or exposure to light and air.\n\n### Deamidation\n\nAsparagine and glutamine residues can undergo deamidation, converting to aspartic and glutamic acids respectively. This reaction is influenced by pH, temperature, and the adjacent amino acid sequence.\n\n## Strategies for Improving Stability\n\n- **Lyophilization** \u2014 Removes water and reduces hydrolysis rates\n- **Low temperature storage** \u2014 Slows all degradation pathways\n- **pH optimization** \u2014 Minimizes specific degradation reactions\n- **Protective packaging** \u2014 Limits light and oxygen exposure\n\n## Analytical Methods\n\nStability is typically monitored using:\n\n- HPLC for purity assessment\n- Mass spectrometry for degradation product identification\n- Bioassays for activity retention",
