                'body' => "## Introduction to Peptide HPLC\n\nHigh-Performance Liquid Chromatography is the primary analytical tool for assessing peptide purity. Reversed-phase HPLC (RP-HPLC) using C18 columns is the most common configuration.\n\n## Column Selection\n\nThe choice of column significantly impacts separation quality:\n\n- **C18 columns** \u2014 Most common, good for general peptide analysis\n- **C8 columns** \u2014 Lower hydrophobicity, useful for smaller peptides\n- **C4 columns** \u2014 For larger or more hydrophobic peptides\n- **Phenyl columns** \u2014 Alternative selectivity for aromatic residues\n\n## Mobile Phase Composition\n\n### Solvents\n\n- **Water** with 0.1% TFA \u2014 Standard aqueous phase\n- **Acetonitrile** \u2014 Most common organic modifier\n- **Methanol or isopropanol** \u2014 Alternatives for specific separations\n\n### Ion-Pairing Agents\n\nTrifluoroacetic acid (TFA) is the most widely used ion-pairing agent, improving peak shape and retention. Formic acid is preferred when MS detection is used.\n\n## Gradient Design\n\nA linear gradient from 5% to 60% acetonitrile over 20-30 minutes is a good starting point for most peptides. Adjust based on:\n\n- Peptide length and hydrophobicity\n- Column dimensions\n- Desired resolution\n\n## Data Interpretation\n\nKey parameters to evaluate:\n\n- **Retention time** \u2014 Should be consistent between runs\n- **Peak symmetry** \u2014 Asymmetry factor should be close to 1\n- **Resolution** \u2014 Baseline separation from impurities\n- **Area percent** \u2014 Purity calculation",
