                'body' => "## Overview of Synthesis Methods\n\nPeptide synthesis has evolved significantly since Merrifield introduced solid-phase peptide synthesis (SPPS) in 1963. Today, both solid-phase and liquid-phase methods are used, each with distinct advantages.\n\n## Solid-Phase Peptide Synthesis (SPPS)\n\nSPPS involves anchoring the C-terminal amino acid to an insoluble resin support and building the peptide chain through sequential coupling reactions.\n\n### Advantages\n\n- Rapid synthesis of peptides up to 50 residues\n- Easy purification by filtration after each step\n- Amenable to automation\n- Suitable for parallel synthesis of multiple peptides\n\n### Limitations\n\n- Aggregation can occur with difficult sequences\n- Excess reagents required for complete coupling\n- Final cleavage can cause side reactions\n\n## Liquid-Phase Peptide Synthesis (LPPS)\n\nLPPS is performed entirely in solution, without a solid support.\n\n### Advantages\n\n- Better suited for large-scale production\n- Easier reaction monitoring in real time\n- No cleavage step required\n- Fewer purification steps overall\n\n### Limitations\n\n- More labor-intensive\n- Requires precipitation or extraction between steps\n- Less suitable for automation\n\n## Choosing the Right Method\n\n- **SPPS** \u2014 Preferred for research-scale synthesis (up to 50 residues)\n- **LPPS** \u2014 Better for industrial-scale production or short peptides\n- **Hybrid approaches** \u2014 Combine both methods for complex targets",
